# Custom Page Interactive Sections Spec

## Scope

Schema-designed forms, Q&A, surveys, polls, and voting embedded as custom-page
sections, including submissions, moderation, results, permissions, and realtime UI.

## Load when

Changing interactive section types, page-content validation, response/ballot APIs,
results visibility, page ownership/editor permissions, or interactive-section UI.

## Owns

- Planned backend domain: `backend/internal/pageinteraction/`
- Models and migrations: `backend/models/`, `backend/internal/migrations/`
- Registry/validation: `backend/internal/s_registry/`
- Builder/renderers: `frontend/src/components/page/`
- Shared results table: `frontend/src/components/ui/TableView/`
- Planned API prefix: `/api/pages/{pageId}/interactive-sections/{sectionKey}`

## Architecture

- Interactive content extends the existing `PageSection` registry and renderer;
  it is not a parallel page system or a datasource workaround.
- Registered types are `form`, `qa`, `survey`, `poll`, and `vote`.
- Every interactive section config has an immutable UUID `section_key`, a
  `schema_version`, presentation settings, audience policy, result policy, and
  type-specific definition. Keys must be unique within a page.
- `pages.content` remains the builder document. On page create/update, the page
  service validates definitions and transactionally reconciles a normalized
  runtime projection. Removed sections become archived so their records remain
  manageable; copying a section always creates a new key and no records.
- Submitted records store a schema snapshot/version, so an expanded historical
  row can render the exact disabled form that produced it after later edits.
- Use `handler => service => repository`. REST owns reads/mutations; server
  confirmation emits aggregate/count invalidations through the existing singleton
  WebSocket. Private answers, respondent identity, and ballots never enter a
  broadcast payload.

## Persistence contract

| Entity | Required data |
| --- | --- |
| Runtime section | UUID key, page, type, validated definition/settings JSONB, schema version, active/archived state, open/close times, creator, timestamps |
| Response | UUID, section key, respondent user or pseudonymous guest key, schema snapshot, answers JSONB, status, submitted timestamp, soft-deletion metadata |
| Choice selection | Response/ballot, question key, option key, rank where applicable; normalized for safe aggregates |
| Q&A item | Question, author/guest identity, moderation state, answer, answerer, pinned/answered timestamps, soft-deletion metadata |
| Participation ledger | Section, participant identity hash/user, attempt, idempotency key, timestamp; enforces configured limits without exposing secret choices |

- Foreign keys cascade only when the page is intentionally purged. Routine record
  deletion is soft delete with audit metadata; a separately authorized retention
  job may permanently purge expired data.
- Index page/key/time, active records, respondent lookups, moderation state, and
  normalized option aggregates. List endpoints are cursor-paginated and bounded.
- Anonymous secret voting separates eligibility/participation from ballot choices;
  no row or event may make a secret ballot attributable to a participant.

## Section contracts

| Type | Participant experience | Manager/result experience |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Form | Schema-driven fields, validation, optional receipt and own submitted read-only view | Search/filter/export-ready `TableView`; configured summary columns; expandable exact disabled form; audited record deletion |
| Q&A | Ask a question and view allowed published/pinned/answered items; optional authenticated upvote | Moderation queue, answer/edit/publish/pin/archive/delete, status/count summaries |
| Survey | Multi-question/branching flow, progress, saved draft only when enabled, confirmation and own response | Completion/funnel and per-question charts/tables; response table when anonymity policy permits |
| Poll | One or more configured choices, clear participation state, results according to policy | Counts, percentages, total responses, abstentions; option management locks after participation begins |
| Vote | Explicit ballot review/confirm flow; single, approval, or ranked mode; receipt proves participation but not secret choice | Open/closed state, turnout, invalid/abstain totals, appropriate tally UI; final results immutable after close unless an audited recount is started |

`qa` means questions and answers, not software quality assurance.

## Definition and lifecycle

- Common settings: title/help/success text, layout/theme-safe style targets,
  audience (`public`, `authenticated`, allowlisted roles), response limit, result
  visibility, anonymity, open/close schedule, retention, notifications, and closed
  state copy.
- Stable question/field/option UUID keys survive reordering and label changes.
- Supported form fields initially include short/long text, email, phone, URL,
  number, date/time, select, multi-select, radio, checkbox, consent, and rating.
  Survey adds scale/NPS/matrix and branching. File input is a gated follow-up that
  must reuse upload ownership/quota/type checks and malware policy.
- Server validation is canonical: required/length/range/pattern/choice membership,
  branching reachability, option cardinality, duplicate keys, schedules, audience,
  and payload/field limits. Client validation mirrors it for feedback only.
- Structural changes after the first response create a new schema version. Poll
  options and open voting ballots cannot be destructively edited; clone/version
  instead. Closing is idempotent and uses server time.
- Vote definitions lock an eligibility snapshot, quorum rule, versioned tally
  algorithm (plurality, approval, or instant-runoff for ranked ballots), and a
  deterministic tie rule before opening. Recounts preserve inputs and audit both
  the old and new result artifacts.

## Authorization and privacy

- Page visibility is checked before section access. Participation policy is an
  additional restriction and cannot make a private page public.
- Admin, page owner, and current page editor can manage records and view manager
  results. Backend policy is centralized and checked for every list/read/export,
  moderate, close/reopen, and delete operation; frontend flags are UX only.
- Participants can read their own response only when enabled. They cannot enumerate
  others. Anonymous responses never expose identity to managers when configured as
  anonymous; explain this irreversibility before activation.
- Guest participation uses a signed, HttpOnly scoped token plus rate limiting and
  abuse controls. It is a deterrent, not a guarantee of one human/one response;
  formal votes default to authenticated eligibility.
- Do not put sensitive answers in URLs, logs, analytics, audit-event metadata,
  caches, notifications, or WS events. Escape plain text and sanitize any allowed
  rich content. CSV export must neutralize spreadsheet formulas.
- Record reads/exports/deletes, moderation, lifecycle changes, and recounts are
  audited. Destructive and privacy-sensitive actions require confirmation; bulk
  operations report partial failures.

## Results and UI contract

- Managers see section-local tabs: `Participate/Preview`, `Responses` or
  `Moderation`, `Results`, and `Design`. Non-managers see only policy-allowed views.
- Result visibility supports `never`, `after_participation`, `after_close`, and
  `always`; managers always receive authorized results. The API returns capabilities
  and result state, not hidden raw data that CSS merely conceals.
- Form/survey rows use the shared `TableView` with search, filters, server sorting,
  pagination, column selection, selection/bulk delete, empty/loading/error states,
  and an accessible expandable detail row. On narrow screens, rows become labeled
  summaries with the same actions and detail content.
- Poll/vote results use accessible totals, percentages and text labels alongside
  charts; never rely on color alone. Q&A uses a readable public feed plus a dense
  moderation table. Dates use local display with server-time semantics.
- Builder design supports drag/reorder, field settings, conditional-logic checks,
  summary-column selection, result-policy preview, desktop/mobile preview, undo-safe
  edits, and explicit publish/close warnings. All CSS uses existing tokens.
- Keyboard operation, focus restoration after row expansion/modals, semantic
  fieldsets/legends, described errors, reduced motion, and screen-reader live status
  are required. Submission is idempotent and resistant to double-click/retry.

## API and realtime contract

- Public/capability reads resolve page + section together; never accept a bare
  section key without verifying its page.
- Separate participant endpoints (definition/state, submit, own response, public
  results/Q&A) from manager endpoints (records, detail, moderation, lifecycle,
  export/delete). Return stable machine-readable validation codes.
- Mutations accept an idempotency key and use transactions for limit checks,
  response/selection writes, and aggregates. Concurrent final submissions cannot
  exceed configured capacity or vote once limits.
- WS events carry only `{ page_id, section_key, action, aggregate_revision }` and
  direct capability-safe updates. Clients refetch authorized aggregates/rows and
  merge into section-local state; no polling and no second socket.

## Verify

- Backend unit/integration tests: schema validation/versioning, authorization matrix,
  anonymity, idempotency/concurrency, schedules, aggregation, soft delete, pagination,
  private-page access, and audit emission.
- Frontend tests: builder validation, each participant state, results-policy gates,
  expanded disabled historical form, manager delete, realtime invalidation, keyboard
  flow, responsive table/cards, loading/empty/error/offline/retry states.
- Commands: `env GOCACHE=/tmp/skaia-go-cache GOTMPDIR=/tmp JWT_SECRET=test-secret go test ./...`
  and, from `frontend/`, `npm run lint`, targeted `npm test`, and `npm run build`.

